    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The New Fellini Spectacle</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Patti Wollman letter about Jan 21 article says Americans avoid foreign films because real life is hard enough</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Whole World Is Watching, Why Aren't Americans?'' by A. O. Scott [Jan. 21]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Whole World Is Watching, Why Aren't Americans?'' by A. O. Scott [Jan. 21]:</p>
        <p>It is no surprise that Americans stay away from today's foreign films. My generation grew up watching the great films of Ingmar Bergman, Fran√ßois Truffaut and Federico Fellini. But it was easier then to spend two hours visiting a difficult universe, because we returned to a less hostile world. With war in Iraq, genocide in Darfur, global warming and the constant threat of terrorism, why watch a movie about the slow death of an alcoholic in Romania? Instead we tune in to this generation's version of a Fellini movie: ''American Idol.'' It has freakish-looking people who provide the eerie music themselves. Honestly, real life is hard enough.</p>
        <p>Patti Wollman  Manhattan</p>
        <p>FOREIGN FILMS</p>
      </block>
